"Just How Hard Are Rotations of  {Z}^n? Algorithms and Cryptography with the Simplest Lattice.","1","[Szy03] Michael Szydlo. Hypercubic lattice reduction and analysis of GGH and NTRU signatures. In EUROCRYPT, 2003. 1, 4 A Proof of Lemma 2.1 We ﬁrst study the expectation of (X mod Z)2 for X ∼Ds. We then use the Chernoﬀ-Hoeﬀding (Lemma 2.14) bound to obtain the result. For t ∈(−1/2, 1/2], let p(t) := (1/s) · P z∈Z ρs(t + z) be the probability density function of X mod Z ∈(−1/2, 1/2]. By the Poisson summation formula, we have p(t) = X w∈Z ρ1/s(w) cos(2πwt) = 1 + 2 cos(2πt) exp(−πs2) + 2 ∞ X w=2 cos(2πwt)ρ1/s(w) . We write f(t) := 2 P∞ w=2 cos(2πwt)ρ1/s(w) It follows that E X∼Ds[(X mod Z)2] = Z 1/2 −1/2 t2p(t) dt = 1/12 −exp(−πs2) π2 + Z 1/2 −1/2 t2f(t) dt . Notice that |f(t)| < 2 exp(−4πs2) + 2 Z ∞ 2 ρ1/s(w) dw ≤2 exp(−4πs2) + Z ∞ 2 wρ1/s(w) dw = exp(−4πs2)(2 + 1/(2πs2)) . 32 Therefore, µ := E X∼Ds[(X mod Z)2] = 1 12 −exp(−πs2) π2 + χ , for some χ with |χ| ≤exp(−4πs2) · (2 + 1/(2πs2)) Z 1/2 −1/2 t2 dt = exp(−4πs2) 12 · (2 + 1/(2πs2)) ≤ε0 . By the Chernoﬀ-Hoeﬀding bound (Lemma 2.14), Pr X∼Dn s [|dist(X, Zn)2 −µn| ≥δn] = Pr h X (Xi mod Z)2 −µn ≥δn i ≤2 exp(−δ2n/10) . It follows that Pr X∼Dn s [|dist(X, Zn)2 −ν| ≥εn] ≤ Pr X∼Dn s [|dist(X, Zn)2 −µn| ≥(ε −ε0)n] ≤2 exp(−(ε −ε0)2n/10) , as needed. B Proof of Theorem 5.2 We next state a key result on lattice sparsiﬁcation that we will use to prove Theorem 5.2. Roughly speaking, it implies that if we sample a random sublattice L′ of prime index p of a lattice L, and 1 < Nprim(L, r) ≲p/ log p then L′ contains a given primitive lattice vector x0 ∈L and no other primitive vectors in L of norm at most r with probability around 1/p. Theorem B.1 ([Ste16a, Theorem 4.1]). For any lattice L ⊆Rn with basis B, r > 0, primitive lattice vectors x0, x1, . . . , xN ∈Lprim satisfying ∥xi∥≤r for all i and xi ̸= ±x0 for all i > 0, and prime p ≥101, if Nprim(L, r) ≤p/(20 log p) then 1 p −N p2 ≤Pr[⟨a, B−1x0⟩≡0 (mod p) and ⟨a, B−1xi⟩̸≡0 (mod p) ∀i > 0] ≤1 p , where a ∈Zn p is chosen uniformly at random. We now restate and prove Theorem 5.2. Theorem 5.2. For any γ = γ(n) ≥1 and r > 0, there is a polynomial-time randomized algorithm with access to a γ-uSVP oracle that takes as input (a basis of a) lattice L and an integer A′ ≥A := Nprim(L, γr) and outputs a vector y ∈L such that if x ∈L is a primitive vector with ∥x∥≤r then Pr[y = x] ≥ 1 200A′ log(100A′) . Furthermore, the algorithm makes a single query to its γ-uSVP oracle on a full-rank sublattice of L. Proof. We assume without loss of generality that r ≥λ1(L). Otherwise, the claim is vacuous because there are no primitive lattice vectors of norm less than λ1(L), i.e., 0 is not primitive. Additionally, we assume without loss of generality that the γ-uSVP oracle always returns a lattice vector even when the lattice generated by its input basis does not satisfy γ-uSVP promise. Let B be the input basis of L, and let n be the rank of L. The algorithm ﬁrst computes a prime p satisfying 50A′ log(100A′) ≤p ≤100A′ log(100A′). It then samples a ∼Zn p uniformly at random and computes a basis B′ of the sublattice L′ := {v ∈L : ⟨B−1v, a⟩≡0 (mod p)} . 33 Next, it calls the γ-uSVP oracle on B′, and receives as output a vector y ∈L. Finally, it returns y. Computing a valid prime p can be done eﬃciently by repeatedly sampling a uniformly random integer in the range [50A′ log(100A′), 100A′ log(100A′)] and testing whether it is prime. Additionally, B′ can be computed eﬃciently given B, p, and a (see, e.g., [Ste16a, Claim 2.15]). So, the algorithm runs in polynomial time and makes a single call to its γ-uSVP oracle, as claimed. We next show correctness. Let x0 := x, and let x1, . . . , xA−1 be primitive vectors in L satisfying xi ̸= ±xj for all 0 ≤i < j ≤A −1. Deﬁne the event E0 := [x0 ∈L′ and x1, . . . , xA−1 /∈L′] . Because Nprim(L, γr) = A, if E0 holds then x0 is the unique (up to sign) primitive vector in L′ of norm at most γr. So, if E0 holds, L′ meets the γ-uSVP promise, and the γ-uSVP oracle must return y = x = x0. We will use Theorem B.1 to lower bound Pr[E0], but in order to apply it we need to show that A′ ≤ p/(20 log p). Using the fact that 50A′ log(100A′) ≤p ≤100A′ log(100A′), for this to hold it suﬃces to have 50A′ log(100A′) 20 log(100A′ log(100A′)) ≥A′ , and this holds because 20 log(100A′ log(100A′) ≤40 log(100A′). So, by Theorem B.1 we have Pr[E0] ≥1 p −A −1 p2 ≥1 p −A′ p2 ≥1 p − 1 50 log(100A′)p ≥1 2p ≥ 1 200A′ log(100A′) , as needed. 34"
